The performance of the developed fluorescent aptasensor based on N-CDs-Apt/β-Co(OH)2 nanoplates, was further investigated under the optimized conditions. The fluorescence signal became stronger with increased PAT concentration (Fig. 4
                        A). Within the range of 0.00125–50 ng/mL, the change in fluorescence intensity showed a proportional relationship with the logarithm of the PAT concentration. The linear equation was ΔF = 52.13log(CPAT/ng mL−1) + 209.92, with a regression coefficient of R2 = 0.9950 (Fig. 4B). Based on three times the standard deviation of ten blank measurements, the calculated limit of detection (LOD) for the as-fabricated fluorescent aptasensor was found to be as low as 0.57 pg/mL. It was observed that the proposed aptasensor had a wide linear range and a low detection limit compared to other aptasensing methods (Table 1
                        ). Moreover, there were several notable advantages to this study's fluorescent donor-acceptor pair, including their ease of preparation, safety, chemical stability, and affordability.
